                                <body>                                                
                                                <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.&#8212;<name type="person" key="xx">Private Charles S. Mattox</name>, <name type="organization" key="">Co. H, 12th
                                                                Pennsylvania Reserves</name>, aged 20 years, was wounded
                                                  at the battle of <name type="BATTLE" key="3"><choice><orig>Spottsylvania</orig><reg>Spotsylvania</reg></choice> Court-house, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1864-05-10">May 10th, 1864</date>, by a conoidal ball,
                                                  which fractured and depressed the left parietal
                                                  bone.  He was brought to the <name type="hospital" key="172">Emory Hospital</name>,
                                                                Washington, on <date type="admit" when="1864-05-13">the 13th</date>, in an almost senseless
                                                  condition.  On <date type="operation" when="1864-05-18">the 18th</date>, <name type="person" key="884">Surgeon N. R. Moseley</name>, <name type="organization" key="132">U. S. V.</name>, removed the depressed bone and applied cold water dressings.  The patient revived and continued
                                                  to improve until <date type="injury" when="1864-05-21">the 21st</date>, when he suddenly
                                                  relapsed into a comatose condition, and died on
                                                                <date type="death" when="1864-05-22">the following day</date>.   The history was contributed by
                                                  <name type="person" key="884">Surgeon N. R. Moseley</name>, <name type="organization" key="132">U. S. V.</name> </p>                                                
